<br><br>
Dr. Kali in her letter to Dr. Barry Spatz  has a legitimate point that the Vietnam Generation 60's Project operates very differently than the POV site.  Different is not better or worse.  It is just different.  Dr. Kali  also has the right to operate her site in any way that she chooses.  Personally I have no idea whether her student is correct or not when they state she is one of the most knowledgeable experts on the  60's and the War in Vietnam.  Being on the Internet for eight years doesn’t automatically qualify one as an expert.  Even if it did, experts frequently disagree.   I agree with Kali Tal that too often we do not consider the feeling or effects the war had on the people of Vietnam.  If it was traumatic to our troops imagine how it must have been for the children who grew up in a country knowing only wars and more wars.   Perspective may be very different depending upon where one is at any given time or place in history.  There is an old story about blindfolding people then asking them to describe what it is that their hand has been placed upon (an elephant).  Each one has a very different description depending upon what portion of the animal they were allowed to experience.  The first one’s hand was put on the trunk of the elephant.  Another person touched the body of the elephant.  The third person’s touched the elephant’s tail.  You would not think they were describing the same animal, but they were.  Each person’s perspective on what they were experiencing makes up a part of what is an elephant.  With  the blindfolds off comes the knowledge that they were describing a different perspective on the same animal based upon  their reality.  History that ignores a major perspective is jaundiced and inaccurate.<br><br>
What disturbs me about the Professor Kali Tal's e-mail to Barry Spatz was what appears to be a  prejudice against Vietnam veterans. The letter wasn’t very tactful . . . but then again she probably didn’t know that Dr. Spatz was going to use it to stir the pot at this site. If such statements that were included in Dr. Kali’s letter regarding how particular she is and how few Vietnam veterans she would ever have anything to do with were directed toward  women, racial minorities, an ethnic group, or those persons 40 years or older, there would be screams of discrimination. A historian/academic who chooses to ignore one portion of  history is not being  objective.  There appears to be a bias against Vietnam veterans.  She doesn't question why periodically Vietnam keeps surfacing, she only appears to wish the war and the warriors would gracefully step back in time and fade into history.<br><br>
&quot;A 3rd Serving of Chicken Soup for the Soul,&quot; What’s Really Important, author unknown, reads as follows:<br>
      A few years ago at the Seattle Special Olympics, nine contestants, all physically or mentally disabled, assembled at the starting line for the 100-yard dash.  At the gun they all started out, not exactly in a dash, but with the relish to run the race to the finish and win.<br>
     All, that is, except one boy who stumbled on the asphalt, tumbled over a couple of times, and began to cry.  The other eight heard the boy cry.  They slowed down and paused.  Then they all turned around and went back.  Every one of them.  One girl with Down’s syndrome bent down and kissed him and said, &quot;This will make it better.&quot;  Then all nine linked arms and walked together to the finish line.<br>
     Everyone in the stadium stood, and the cheering went on for 10 minutes.<br>
                                                   Submitted by Bob French<br><br>
Is your response to laugh at this story and say &quot;Could only happen at the Special Olympics! &quot;  Maybe  so. I find that sad.   Healing of this nation’s wounds from Vietnam,  requires those still standing or who have found their way back on their feet to go back, help their brother or sister  up if they haven’t made it on their own. Accept these guys, rather than being afraid of them.  Let them talk and listen to what they have to say.  Then they may be able to say on their own,  tomorrows another day and there will be other races to finish.  We all need to listen to each other whether we are draft dodger, protester, veteran, educator, parents or spouses of veterans . . . etc. <br><br>
Your defense of someone you respect is admirable dear student. A word of warning  though.  Just as we learned at some point that our parents are not always right and are human beings . . .   the same is true of our teachers.   At some time you may become a parent, and even a teacher.  I believe you will come to realize, the same as I,  that the more you know, the more you know you don’t know and  still have to learn and understand.  Do not blindly accept what anyone tells you, supposed expert or not or you could find yourself in a situation similar to what the Vietnam vet experienced having participated in something not because you believed in it but you were told this was the right thing to do.  No one but God, if you believe in a divine being, is all-knowing, all powerful, and perfect.  During the Vietnam Era,  some of us put too much trust in our government.  We were brought up waving the Red, White, and Blue  of the American flag.  After the fact it is easier to say that we should have questioned what we were told we should do and did.  One of the legacies of the 60's was critical thought.  We questioned the status quo.  Even the meek and mild amongst us had a touch of the rebel.  The era not only led to protesting a war but free love and drug experimentation.<br><br>
In the 60s I didn’t count myself a hippy but I wore jeans with flowers painted up one leg, long straight hair, and learned how to play the ukelele and sing folk songs like &quot;“Where have all the young men gone, long time passing . . . &quot;   Didn’t make it to Woodstock but did get to the Newport Jazz festival to listen to the songs of the times, and sleep in the park.  Helped talk kids that got bad drugs or too much of a good thing down from out of control trips. Kept my bra instead of burning it; got rid of the girdle instead. I attended a protest against the war.  Went off to war in the hospital service through the Red Cross.  Saw more blood and guts, heard more stories of horror from our boy/men  than I ever wanted to see or hear in a lifetime. <br><br>
Which portion of the 60's  is easier and more pleasant to remember?  The songs and the good times naturally are easier to remember.  But the negatives of war was part of the era, not just the good times rolling on the river.  There are lessons to be learned from our experiences at home and overseas.  I don’t feel that academic history has adequately explained it yet. I have been waiting for 25 years for the historians and &quot;experts&quot; to make sense out of it so they can tell me.  I have found none.  Maybe I ask for too much, adults have to learn to live with ambiguity and uncertainty but then what are the lessons learned so we are not destined to repeat the errors?  Do we learn never to get involved in other people’s fights, or do we learn to throw everything we have at the enemy instead of engaging in a limited offensive.  Then we have to ask ourselves what is our responsibility when we see injustices in the world and negotiation and reason haven’t been effective.  All nations will not agree to compromise.  How much are we as a so called civilized society willing to see then ignore when another nation or its citizens are brutalized by a bully or attacked for what they have that the other nation wants? <br><br>
If I have misunderstood Dr. Kali Tal, I am willing to apologize.  Dr. Barry this is not a feminist issue, it is one of humanity.  Please stop trying to stir up strife and pit people against others .   Some woman at PBS is working for free to keep this site open.  The best way you can thank her is to keep up the posts.  Whoever you are that volunteered to keep this site open, even if the plug is pulled in two weeks,  thank you from all of us who visit but haven't let our presence be known before. <br><br>
 Gentlemen.... please carryon until the final pullout.  Don't give up prematurely.  <br><br>

